snippet.textDisplay:
Love this video; the openness. Especially your angle. Specifically doing it just for connecting and explaining and being honest.
I also noticed you were off with Rach. But your explanation makes perfect sense. I do the same. When I'm first in an situation, I consider myself 100% stuck. Like a meeting at work every week. I don't have to be there, and I only listen. Due to issues I tend to get extreeemely tired at that meeting. The "feeling like I am going to pass out" sort of tired. I am trying desperate to wake up, but literally can't keep my eyes open or head up. So you know, I am sitting there like an idiot falling asleep for 1-2 seconds and waking up as my head is falling, and trying to force my eyes open. Everyone can see it, I am sure. I should just leave. Yes, it will be sorta weird, but a hellofalot better than sitting there bothering everyone doing nothing good to anyone. Yet, in my head it is not an option to leave. Instead I am having the longest hour in history in pure torture. Makes no sense to everyone watching I am sure but at that point I am just so stuck. One of maaaany examples. Everyone is like that to some degree. Totally get it.

snippet.textDisplay: Another Endo woman here.  I was surgically diagnosed in 2016.  We were able to conceive a baby boy naturally after 8 years of trying.  The thing that helped me (I think) is becoming vegetarian, clean eating and regular exercise.  Once I quit eating meat, the next year I was pregnant.  I'm not sure if they are connected, but it's an awful big coincidence.  Now I'm on birth control to stop my periods and my symptoms have gotten 80% better.  The doctors want to try to keep my uterus until I reach 50, but I'm getting to the point I just want to be done with it.

snippet.textDisplay: <3

Thank you so much for speaking about endometriosis! I can completely relate and it’s comforting to have someone who knows what you’re going through talk about it. I’m also a mental health therapist so I get the feeling of having to be “on” and not letting your emotions show/pretending to be happy. It’s very difficult and almost impossible to do some days, like it has been this week. To be a good therapist, You obviously have to separate your own feelings from your clients needs, but sometimes you just can’t because we’re human too, dealing with real crap the same way they are trying to. This is my first YouTube video I’ve ever commented on but I just had to after hearing you talk about it. Just this week I was in the ER for a flare up. I had my first laparoscopic excision surgery almost exactly a year ago, where I almost died and had internal bleeding, and it wasn’t even successful!! Talk about feeling hopeless. There were a lot of complications after my surgery because of the internal bleeding and I don’t think it’s talked about enough (what happens when surgery doesn’t work) Today, I tried a hypogastric nerve block so we will see if I can start to get relief. I post this in solidarity with all my other endo women, you’re not alone, you’re not crazy, and I hope our voices will eventually lead to more research on this devastating disease. I am 1 in 10 ❤️

snippet.textDisplay: I'm glad you brought up Endometriosis. It's a debilitating disease that effects 1 in 10 women. snippet.textDisplay: A few years go my marriage, my health and my mind fell apart right at the birth of my children. I lost an entire life to my ex using drugs and cheating. I fell to pieces. I remember sitting in a puddle of tears and having a panicky moment. My mom and grandma stopped everything and came over and I told them that I didn’t understand why I couldn’t hold it together like they did. They both laughed and told me things they went through and what they did. It made me feel so much better to know that I could still be strong but be going through a hard time. A tough day is a tough day and it’s ok to be sad and freak out. The strength comes in when you continue to move forward despite how you feel.

snippet.textDisplay: Girl, I feel your pain!  So many people, including doctors, dismissed the severe month;y pain I had. I used to literally pass out, the pain was so bad.
